    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning all yellow and kind of pale. any idea what happened or how to fix it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That's a classic sign of bottom-feeding pests or poor drainage, but it could also be a result of old leaves naturally dying off. You should check for aphids or spider mites on the undersides of those yellowing leaves, as they are the most common culprits for this specific symptom. To fix it, prune off the affected lower leaves to improve air circulation and let the plant focus its energy on the healthy top growth. If you're worried about a more serious issue, you can try a light spray of neem oil or insecticidal soap to keep any hidden pests at bay.\n\nJust remember, in the grand scheme of gardening, the bottom leaves are often just the first to go to the \"dungeon\" of the compost heap, which is a very natural process for the plant. However, if the whole plant looks pale and the soil is soggy, it might be a sign of root rot, which is a bit more serious. In that case, check your drainage holes and ensure the soil isn't staying too wet for too long.\n\nGardening is full of surprises, but with a little bit of detective work, you can usually figure out what's going on. If you're still not sure,",
